<P>
Correction Appended 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 95; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
141 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARKOWITZ'S MESSAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Someone at Calendar either has a peculiarly nasty sense of humor or has simply 
not been paying attention. Allowing Charles Markowitz to write about a 
playwright is like asking a skinhead to do a piece on the local rabbi ("When 
Reel and Real-Life Merge Into One Image," April 2). 
</P>
<P>
Markowitz has built a career by expressing his contempt for playwrights, 
assaulting script after script in exercises that resemble drive-by shootings 
more than productions. 
</P>
<P>
There may be legitimacy to this approach to theater, but it makes him a curious 
choice to do an article on any playwright, much less Tom Stoppard. 
</P>
<P>
I wouldn't ask The Times to protect playwrights (Lord knows that critic Dan 
Sullivan isn't much help), but when a writer's bias is so extreme as 
Markowitz's, you're only asking for incompetence; Markowitz delivers. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID LINK 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
April 16, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
In early copies of the April 9 Calendar, David Link's letter contained an 
incorrect article reference, the result of an editing error. Link's letter was 
about Charles Marowitz, the author of an April 2 article on playwright Tom 
Stoppard, not about Robert Markowitz, who also had an article in the issue. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
