<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNFAIR PROPERTY TAX BASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So the grandchildren aren't living as well as the grandparents -- what's wrong 
with that? 
</P>
<P>
Today's "children" want it all, now. Mom and dad did not start out with what 
they now have. They worked hard for it. 
</P>
<P>
Their children want $300,000-$400,000 homes with a BMW in the driveway, not 
what Ms. Goodman calls "affordable" housing. 
</P>
<P>
Great, let's get rid of Proposition 13 and tax old mom and dad right out of 
their home. After all, if the kids can't live in the manner in which they are 
accustomed why should the old folks? 
</P>
<P>
KATHLEEN STANLEY 
</P>
<P>
Agoura Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040989-0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 41522 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 9, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part 5; Page 4; Column 4; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
123 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNFAIR PROPERTY TAX BASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The family home sits on an unfair tax base" with widely varying assessments up 
and down the block, the result of a taxpayer revolt against being taxed on 
paper profits by tax-omnivorous public agencies. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed solution? 
</P>
<P>
Since the stay-putters (Stall's term) aren't willing to give up the benefits of 
Proposition 13, knowing that to do so would move much of the middle-class 
slowly but surely into the "homeless" category, why not sneak up on them by 
letting "stay-putters' homes to grow at a slightly faster rate than the present 
maximum 2%, but keep them capped at a reasonable rate. . . . The equity gap 
would be closed over the years." 
</P>
<P>
Sounds like a progressive repeal of Proposition 13. 
</P>
<P>
JOHN CARL BROGDON 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
