<P>
JULIAN LENNON: "MR. JORDAN." ATLANTIC * 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE BOEHM 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sometimes he sounds like his dad, which is natural enough. Sometimes he affects 
the deep-voiced theatricality of the post-punk legion ofDavid Bowie imitators. 
But, most of all, Julian Lennon sounds here as if he hasn't an original thought 
in his head, nor any expressive means that transcend cliche. Producer Patrick 
Leonard tries to keep it interesting with a host of studio tricks and a small 
army of supporting players, but all that isn't worth much if the key songwriter 
doesn't dare to imagine. In the course of three albums, Lennon has gone from 
winsome to forgettable to soporific. MIKE BOEHM 
</P>
