</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DAVIS CUP ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CZECHS WIN IN DOUBLES FOR 2-1 LEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Czechoslovakia took a 2-1 lead over defending champion West Germany in their 
Davis Cup World Group quarterfinal by winning the doubles match in five sets 
Saturday at Prague, Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
Milan Srejber and Petr Korda beat Boris Becker and Eric Jelen, 6-3, 6-7 (2-7), 
3-6, 7-6 (9-7), 6-3, in 3 hours 47 minutes to put Czechoslovakia one victory 
away from the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
In today's deciding singles, Srejber takes on Becker while Carl-Uwe Steeb plays 
Karel Novacek of Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
The West Germans need to take both singles to win. The winner of the Prague 
match will meet the United States in the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
In the fourth-set tiebreaker, a linesman nearly handed the match to West 
Germany when he called Srejber for a foot fault. Srejber then double-faulted, 
and Jelen had the chance to close out the match. But he netted a simple volley 
and then double-faulted. 
</P>
<P>
Becker, who served 22 aces in beating Novacek in straight sets in the opening 
singles Friday, dropped his serve for the third time to give the Czechs a 2-0 
lead in the final set. Becker had only six aces Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Srejber, who defeated Steeb in straight sets Friday, served out the match on 
his first match point when Jelen netted a return. 
</P>
<P>
Stefan Edberg and Anders Jarryd beat Horst Skoff and Alexander Antonitsch, 6-3, 
6-1, 6-3, to give Sweden a 2-1 lead over Austria in their quarterfinal at 
Vienna. 
</P>
<P>
Friday, Skoff upset Mats Wilander in a six-hour marathon match, 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 
(9-7), 1-6, 6-4, 9-7, after Edberg overpowered Antonitsch, 6-3, 6-2, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
Two Yugoslav 6-footers fired a total of 27 aces to give Yugoslavia an 
unbeatable 3-0 lead over Spain in their quarterfinal at Split, Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
Slobodan Zivojinovic and Goran Ivanisevic defeated Emilio Sanchez and Sergio 
Casal, 4-6, 6-4, 4-6, 7-6 (7-5), 13-11, in a four-hour battle. 
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia will next play the Sweden-Austria winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
